# Controller Layer

## Responsibility

Controllers handle HTTP only: parse request, validate input, call service, return response. No business logic.

## Structure

- One controller per resource (e.g. `ItemController`, `UserController`).
- Base path: `@RequestMapping("/api/v1/{resource}")` (versioned).
- Use `@RestController`; use `@RequiredArgsConstructor` + constructor-injected service(s).
- Return `ResponseEntity<T>` for explicit status and headers; use `ResponseEntity.ok()`, `.status(CREATED)`, `.noContent()`, etc.

## Request & Response

- **Never expose entities.** Use DTOs: `*Request` for body input, `*Response` or `*Dto` for output.
- Validate request bodies with `@Valid` (or `@Validated`) and Bean Validation (`@NotNull`, `@Size`, `@Min`, etc.).
- Path/query params: use `@PathVariable`, `@RequestParam` with sensible defaults; document required vs optional.

```java
// ✅ GOOD
@PostMapping
public ResponseEntity<ItemResponse> create(@Valid @RequestBody CreateItemRequest request) {
    ItemResponse created = itemService.create(request);
    return ResponseEntity.status(CREATED).body(created);
}

@GetMapping("/{id}")
public ResponseEntity<ItemResponse> getById(@PathVariable Long id) {
    return ResponseEntity.ok(itemService.findById(id));
}
```

## HTTP Semantics

- GET: 200 + body, or 404 (handle in `@ControllerAdvice`).
- POST: 201 + body + `Location` header when creating a resource.
- PUT/PATCH: 200 + body, or 404.
- DELETE: 204 No Content, or 404.
- Use proper status codes; avoid returning 200 for failures.

## Don’t

- Put business logic in controllers (delegate to service).
- Catch exceptions to return error JSON here; use `@ControllerAdvice`.
- Return raw entities or domain types; always map to DTOs.
